or the code, stay for the community.','','none'),(9149,_binary 'There are a few ways to get started with Drupal:','','none'),(9150,_binary '<a href=\"@drupal_user_guide\">User Guide:</a> Includes installing, administering, site building, and maintaining the content of a Drupal website.','','none'),(9151,_binary '<a href=\"@create_content\">Create Content:</a> Want to get right to work? Start adding content. <strong>Note:</strong> the information on this page will go away once you add content to your site. Read on and bookmark resources of interest.','','none'),(9152,_binary '<a href=\"@drupal_extend\">Extend Drupal:</a> Drupal’s core software can be extended and customized in remarkable ways. Install additional functionality and change the look of your site using addons contributed by our community.','','none'),(9153,_binary 'Bookmark these links to our active Drupal community groups and support resources.','','none'),(9154,_binary '<a href=\"@drupal_global_training_days\">Global Training Days:</a> Helpful information for evaluating Drupal as a framework and as a career path. Taught in your local language.','','none'),(9155,_binary '<a href=\"@drupal_events\">Upcoming Events:</a> Learn and connect with others at conferences and events held around the world.','','none'),(9156,_binary '<a href=\"@drupal_community\">Community Page:</a> List of key Drupal community groups with their own content.','','none'),(9157,_binary 'Get support and chat with the Drupal community on <a href=\"@drupal_slack\">Slack</a> or <a href=\"@drupal_chat\">DrupalChat</a>. When you’re looking for a solution to a problem, go to <a href=\"@drupal_answers\">Drupal Answers on Stack Exchange</a>.','','none'),(9158,_binary 'Migration failed with source plugin exception: @e in @file line @line','','none'),(9159,_binary 'Display %display has set node/% as path. This will not produce what you want. If you want to have multiple versions of the node view, use Layout Builder.','','none'),(9160,_binary 'See <a href=\"https://www.php.net/manual/datetime.format.php#refsect1-datetime.format-parameters\" target=\"_blank\">the documentation for PHP date formats</a>.','','none'),(9161,_binary 'The specified file \'%original_source\' could not be copied because the destination directory \'%destination_directory\' is not properly configured. This may be caused by a problem with file or directory permissions.','','none'),(9162,_binary 'A user-defined date format. See the <a href=\"https://www.php.net/manual/datetime.format.php#refsect1-datetime.format-parameters\">PHP manual</a> for available options.','','none'),(9163,_binary 'Manage translations for any entity that the user can edit','','none'),(9164,_binary 'The Filter module allows administrators to configure text formats. Text formats change how HTML tags and other text will be <em>processed and displayed</em> in the site. They are used to transform text, and also help to defend your website against potentially damaging input from malicious users. Visual text editors can be associated with text formats by using the <a href=\":editor_help\">Text Editor module</a>. For more information, see the <a href=\":filter_do\">online documentation for the Filter module</a>.','','none'),(9165,_binary 'Enabling the Forum module provides a default <em>Forums</em> menu link in the Tools menu that links to the <a href=\":forums\">Forums page</a>.','','none'),(9166,_binary 'There are four main types of data. <em>Content</em> is the information (text, images, etc.) meant to be displayed to website visitors. <em>Configuration</em> is data that defines how the content is displayed; some configuration (such as field labels) may also be visible to site visitors. <em>State</em> is temporary data about the state of your site, such as the last time the system <em>cron</em> jobs ran. <em>Session</em> is a subset of State information, related to users\' interactions with the site, such as site cookies and whether or not they are logged in.','','none'),(9167,_binary 'List (Options module): Stores values chosen from pre-defined lists, where the values can be numbers or text; see section below for more on list fields.','','none'),(9168,_binary 'Reference (core system): Stores entity references; see section above','','none'),(9169,_binary 'Text (Text module): Stores formatted and unformatted text; see section below for more on text fields.','','none'),(9170,_binary 'What settings are available for List field types?','','none'),(9171,_binary 'List fields associate pre-defined <em>keys</em> (or value codes) with <em>labels</em> that the user sees. For example, you might define a list field that shows the user the names of several locations, while behind the scenes a location code is stored in the database. Each list field type corresponds to one type of stored key. For example, a <em>List (integer)</em> field stores integers, while the <em>List (text)</em> field stores text strings. Once you have chosen the field type, the main setting for a list field is the <em>Allowed values</em> list, which associates the keys with the labels.','','none'),(9172,_binary 'What types of Text fields are available?','','none'),(9173,_binary 'There are several types of text fields, with different characteristics. Text fields can be either <em>plain</em> or <em>formatted</em>: plain text fields do not contain HTML, while formatted fields can contain HTML and are processed through <em>text filters</em> (these are provided by the core Filter module; if you have that module enabled, see the related topic below on filters for more information). Text fields can also be regular-length (with a limit of 255 characters) or <em>long</em> (with a very large character limit), and long formatted text fields can include a <em>summary</em> attribute. All possible combinations of these characteristics exist as text field types; for example, <em>Text (plain)</em> and <em>Text (formatted, long, with summary)</em> are two examples of text field types.','','none'),(9174,_binary 'What is a menu?','','none'),(9175,_binary 'A menu is a collection of <em>menu links</em> used to navigate a web site. Menus and menu links can be provided by modules or site administrators.','','none'),(9176,_binary 'Managing menus overview','','none'),(9177,_binary 'The core Menu UI module provides a user interface for managing menus, including creating new menus, reordering menu links, and disabling links provided by modules. It also provides the ability for links to content items to be added to menus while editing, if configured on the content type. The core Custom Menu Links module provides the ability to add custom links to menus. Each menu can be displayed by placing a block in a theme region; some themes also can display a menu outside of the block system. See the related topics listed below for specific tasks.','','none'),(9178,_binary '<a href=\"https://www.drupal.org/docs/user_guide/en/menu-concept.html\">User guide page Concept: Menu</a>','','none'),(9179,_binary 'Enabling web services','','none'),(9180,_binary 'What is a web service?','','none'),(9181,_binary 'A web service allows your site to provide its content and data to other web sites and applications. Typically, the data is transported via <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hypertext_Transfer_Protocol\">HTTP</a> in a serialized machine-readable format.','','none'),(9182,_binary 'What is serialization?','','none'),(9183,_binary 'Serialization is the process of converting complex data structures into text strings, so that they can be exchanged and stored. The reverse process is called <em>deserialization</em>. JSON and XML are the two most-commonly-used data serialization formats for web services.','','none'),(9184,_binary 'What is HTTP Basic authentication?','','none'),(9185,_binary '<a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Basic_access_authentication\">HTTP Basic authentication</a> is a method for authenticating requests by sending a user name and password along with the request.','','none'),(9186,_binary 'What modules provide web services?','','none'),(9187,_binary 'The following Drupal core modules provide web services:','','none'),(9188,_binary 'JSON:API module','','none'),(9189,_binary 'RESTful Web Services module','','none'),(9190,_binary 'Serialization module','','none'),(9191,_binary 'Provides a framework for adding specific serialization formats for other modules to use.','','none'),(9192,_binary 'HTTP Basic Authentication module','','none'),(9193,_binary 'Provides a way for web services to be authenticated using HTTP Basic authentication against Drupal user accounts.','','none'),(9194,_binary 'There are also contributed modules that provide web services.','','none'),(9195,_binary 'Online documentation for the RESTful Web Services module','','none'),(9196,_binary 'Online documentation for the JSON:API module','','none'),(9197,_binary 'Comparison of the RESTFul Web Services and JSON:API modules','','none'),(9198,_binary 'Connecting text editors to text formats','','none'),(9199,_binary 'What is a text editor?','','none'),(9200,_binary 'Managing text filters and text formats','','none'),(9201,_binary 'What are text filters and text formats?','','none'),(9202,_binary 'A text filter is a processing step that can be applied to text, either to transform it in some way (such as converting URLs in the text into HTML links), or to defend against potentially-dangerous input from site users. A text format is an ordered sequence of text filters. Text filters are provided by modules; text formats are managed by the core Filter module.','','none'),(9203,_binary 'Text fields that have \"formatted\" in the field type name, such as <em>Text (formatted)</em>, use text formats. Users choose the text format when editing the field text; when the field text is shown on the site, it is processed by the chosen text format. Administrators can configure text formats and assign permissions for who can use each format. If the core Text Editor module is enabled, administrators can also associate visual editors with text formats.','','none'),(9204,_binary 'What text filters are available?','','none'),(9205,_binary 'Some of the more commonly used text filters are:','','none'),(9206,_binary 'Limits which HTML tags can be used; useful both for site security and enforcing site design.','','none'),(9207,_binary 'Line breaks in HTML source are displayed as horizontal spaces. This filter converts line breaks into HTML paragraph and line break tags.','','none'),(9208,_binary 'Takes plain URLs in text and turns them into HTML links.','','none'),(9209,_binary 'For text formats that allow HTML image tags, restricts images to URLs within this site.','','none'),(9210,_binary 'Click <em>Configure</em> to configure an existing text format, or <em>+ Add text format</em> to create a new text format.','','none'),(9211,_binary 'Enter the desired <em>Name</em> for the text format.','','none'),(9212,_binary 'Check the <em>Roles</em> that can use this text format. Some HTML tags allow users to embed malicious links or scripts in text. To ensure security, anonymous and untrusted users should only have access to text formats that restrict them to either plain text or a safe set of HTML tags. <strong>Improper text format configuration is a security risk.</strong>','','none'),(9213,_binary 'If the core Text Editor module is installed, see the related topic to connect a text editor to this text format.','','none'),(9214,_binary 'Under <em>Enabled filters</em>, check the text filters that you want to use.','','none'),(9215,_binary 'Under <em>Filter processing order</em>, drag the filters to the correct order. Choose the order carefully; for example, if you have a filter that results in a particular HTML tag being added to the text, that should run after a filter that restricts HTML tags, to avoid deleting the new tags the first filter added.','','none'),(9216,_binary 'Under <em>Filter settings</em>, verify and adjust the settings for each active filter that has configuration options.','','none'),(9217,_binary 'Click <em>Save configuration</em>, which will return you to the <em>Text formats and editors</em> page.','','none'),(9218,_binary 'Repeat these steps if you have additional text formats to configure.','','none'),(9219,_binary 'Creating threaded discussion forums','','none'),(9220,_binary 'What is a forum?','','none'),(9221,_binary 'A forum is nested hierarchy of discussions, where users post topics and comment on them.','','none'),(9222,_binary 'What is the forum hierarchy?','','none'),(9223,_binary 'The forum hierarchy consists of:','','none'),(9224,_binary 'Optional <em>containers</em> can be used to group similar forums (for example, <em>Recipes</em>). Forums can be inside containers and vice versa.','','none'),(9225,_binary '<em>Comments</em> submitted by users (for example, <em>You wash the potatoes first and then...</em>).','','none'),(9226,_binary 'The <em>forums</em> and <em>containers</em> in the hierarchy are implemented as terms in a hierarchical taxonomy vocabulary. The topics are content items posted in forums (not in containers), and replies are comments on each topic item. Deeply nested hierarchies of forums and containers are generally difficult for users to understand and navigate, so it is recommended to keep your hierarchy simple.','','none'),(9227,_binary 'Managing and using forums overview','','none'),(9228,_binary 'The core Forum module supplies a content type called <em>Forum topic</em>, along with associated comment type and taxonomy vocabulary. As with other comment types, you can configure comments on forum topics to be threaded or unthreaded. See the related topics listed below for specific tasks.','','none'),(9229,_binary 'Configuring forums','','none'),(9230,_binary 'Configure settings for forums, and set up forum structure.','','none'),(9231,_binary 'Choose the desired settings for <em>Hot topic threshold</em>, <em>Topics per page</em>, and <em>Default order</em>. Click <em>Save configuration</em> if you have made any changes.','','none'),(9232,_binary 'Create the containers that you want in your forum hierarchy, starting at the top level, if any. To create a container, click <em>Add container</em>, enter the container name and optionally other settings, and click <em>Save</em>.','','none'),(9233,_binary 'Create the forums that you want in your forum hierarchy, starting at the top level. To create a forum, click <em>Add forum</em> and enter the forum name. If your hierarchy has this forum inside a container or another forum, select the parent forum/container in the <em>Parent</em> field. Review and/or edit the other settings, and click <em>Save</em>.','','none'),(9234,_binary 'Optionally, delete the provided <em>General discussion</em> forum, if you do not want this forum to be available on your site.','','none'),(9235,_binary 'Review and/or edit the permissions related to forums. The administrative permission for editing the forum settings is in the <em>Forum</em> module section of the permissions page, and administrative permissions for editing the forum hierarchy are in the <em>Taxonomy</em> module section. The user permissions for creating forum topics are in the <em>Node</em> module section, and for commenting on topics are in the <em>Comment</em> module section.','','none'),(9236,_binary 'Locking a forum topic','','none'),(9237,_binary 'Lock a topic to prevent users from making any more comments.','','none'),(9238,_binary 'Locate the topic within the forum, and click on the title to view the topic.','','none'),(9239,_binary 'Click <em>Edit</em>.','','none'),(9240,_binary 'Under <em>Comment settings</em>, check <em>Closed</em>.','','none'),(9241,_binary 'Moving a topic to a new forum','','none'),(9242,_binary 'Move a forum topic and all of its comments to a new forum.','','none'),(9243,_binary 'In the <em>Forums</em> field, select the new forum that you want the topic to move to.','','none'),(9244,_binary 'Check <em>Leave shadow copy</em> to create a link in the original forum pointing to the new location.','','none'),(9245,_binary 'Starting a forum discussion','','none'),(9246,_binary 'Post a new topic in a forum to start a discussion.','','none'),(9247,_binary 'Click <em>Add new Forum topic</em>.','','none'),(9248,_binary 'Enter the topic\'s <em>Subject</em> and <em>Body</em>.','','none'),(9249,_binary 'In the <em>Manage</em> administrative menu, navigate to <em>Structure</em> &gt; <em>Block layout</em>.','','none'),(9250,_binary 'Configure menu settings for a content type','','none'),(9251,_binary 'For an existing content type, configure the available menus that will be shown as options on content editing screens; links to content items of this type can be added to these menus during editing.','','none'),(9252,_binary 'Locate the content type you want to configure, and click <em>Edit</em> in the <em>Operations</em> list.','','none'),(9253,_binary 'Under <em>Menu settings</em>, check the menus that you want to be available when editing a content item of this type.','','none'),(9254,_binary 'Optionally, select the <em>Default parent item</em>, to put links to content items under a default location in the menu structure.','','none'),(9255,_binary 'Click <em>Save content type</em>.','','none'),(9256,_binary 'Adding a link to a menu','','none'),(9257,_binary 'Add a link to a menu. Note that you can also add a link to a menu from the content edit page if menu settings have been configured for the content type.','','none'),(9258,_binary 'Locate the desired menu and click <em>Add link</em> in the <em>Operations</em> list.','','none'),(9259,_binary 'Enter the <em>Menu link title</em> to be displayed.','','none'),(9260,_binary 'Enter the <em>Link</em>, one of the following:','','none'),(9261,_binary 'An internal path, such as <em>/node/add</em>','','none'),(9262,_binary 'A full external URL','','none'),(9263,_binary 'Start typing the title of a content item and select it when the full title comes up','','none'),(9264,_binary '<em>&lt;nolink&gt;</em> to display the <em>Menu link title</em> as plain text without a link','','none'),(9265,_binary '<em>&lt;front&gt;</em> to link to the front page of your site','','none'),(9266,_binary 'Make sure that <em>Enabled</em> is checked; if not, the menu link will not be displayed.','','none'),(9267,_binary 'Optionally, enter a <em>Description</em>, which will be displayed when a user hovers over the link.','','none'),(9268,_binary 'Optionally, check <em>Show as expanded</em> to automatically show the children of this link (if any) when this link is shown.','','none'),(9269,_binary 'Optionally, select the <em>Parent link</em>, if this menu link should be a child of another menu link.','','none'),(9270,_binary 'Click <em>Save</em>. You will be returned to the <em>Add link</em> page to add another link.','','none'),(9271,_binary 'Locate the menu you just added a link to and click <em>Edit</em> in the <em>Operations</em> list.','','none'),(9272,_binary 'Verify that the order of links is correct. If it is not, drag menu links until the order is correct, and click <em>Save</em>.','','none'),(9273,_binary 'Creating a menu','','none'),(9274,_binary 'Create a new menu.','','none'),(9275,_binary 'Click <em>Add menu</em>.','','none'),(9276,_binary 'Enter the title for the menu, which is used as the default block title if the menu is displayed as a block. If desired, also edit the machine name of the menu, which is by default derived from the title.','','none'),(9277,_binary 'Enter an administrative summary, which is displayed on the <em>Menus</em> page.','','none'),(9278,_binary 'If your site has more than one language, choose the language for the menu.','','none'),(9279,_binary 'Click <em>Save</em>. You will be on the menu editing page, ready to add links to the menu if the core Custom Menu Links module is installed; see related topics for further tasks.','','none'),(9280,_binary 'Reordering and disabling menu links','','none'),(9281,_binary 'Disable menu links or change the order and hierarchy of menu links.','','none'),(9282,_binary 'Click <em>Edit menu</em> for the menu that you want to edit.','','none'),(9283,_binary 'Drag menu links into a new order, or check/uncheck <em>Enabled</em> to enable or disable menu links.','','none'),(9284,_binary 'Click <em>Save</em> to save your changes.','','none'),(9285,_binary '<a href=\"https://www.php.net/manual/datetime.format.php#refsect1-datetime.format-parameters\">PHP date format codes reference</a>','','none'),(9286,_binary '[site:name]: The name of your website.','','none'),(9287,_binary '[site:url]: The URL of your website.','','none'),(9288,_binary 'Managing content listings (views)','','none'),(9289,_binary 'What is a view?','','none'),(9290,_binary 'A <em>view</em> is a listing of items on your site; for example, a block showing the most recent comments, a page listing news items, or a list of registered users. The listings can be formatted in a table, grid, list, calendar, RSS feed, and other formats (some output formats may require you to install additional contributed modules).','','none'),(9291,_binary 'What are the components of a view?','','none'),(9292,_binary 'When you first create a view, you will specify what type of <em>base data</em> is being displayed in the view, which cannot be changed. After choosing a base data type, you can edit the following components, which allow you to specify which data to output, in what order, and in what format:','','none'),(9293,_binary '<em>Displays</em>: whether the output goes to a page, block, feed, etc.; a single view can have multiple displays, each with different settings.','','none'),(9294,_binary '<em>Format</em>: the output style for each display, such as content item, grid, table, or HTML list.','','none'),(9295,_binary '<em>Fields</em>: if the Format allows, the particular fields to display.','','none'),(9296,_binary '<em>Filter criteria</em>: criteria to limit the data to output, such as whether the content is published, the type of content, etc. Filters can be <em>exposed</em> to let users choose how to filter the data.','','none'),(9297,_binary '<em>Sort criteria</em>: how to order the data. Sorting can also be exposed to users.','','none'),(9298,_binary '<em>Header</em> and <em>Footer</em>: content to display at the top or bottom of the view display.','','none'),(9299,_binary '<em>No results behavior</em>: what to do if the filter criteria result in having no data to display.','','none'),(9300,_binary '<em>Pager</em>: how many items to display, and how to paginate if there are additional items to display.','','none'),(9301,_binary '<em>Advanced</em> &gt; <em>Contextual filters</em>: like regular filters, except the criteria come from the <em>context</em>, such as the current date, page the view is displayed on, etc.','','none'),(9302,_binary '<em>Advanced</em> &gt; <em>Relationships</em>: additional data to pull in and display, related in some way to the base data of the view (such as data about the user who created the content item).','','none'),(9303,_binary '<em>Advanced</em> &gt; <em>Exposed form</em>: if you have exposed filters or sorts, how to display the form to the user.','','none'),(9304,_binary 'Managing views overview','','none'),(9305,_binary 'The core Views module handles the display of views, and the core Views UI module allows you to create, edit, and delete views in the administrative interface. See the related topics listed below for specific tasks (if the Views UI module is installed).','','none'),(9306,_binary '<a href=\"https://www.drupal.org/docs/user_guide/en/views-chapter.html\">Views chapter in the User Guide</a>','','none'),(9307,_binary 'Adding a new display to an existing view','','none'),(9308,_binary 'Add a new display to an existing view. This will allow you to display similar data to an existing view, using similar settings, in a new block, page, feed, etc.','','none'),(9309,_binary 'Under <em>Displays</em>, click <em>Add</em>.','','none'),(9310,_binary 'In the pop-up list, click the link for the type of display you want to add; the most common types are <em>Page</em> and <em>Block</em>. The new display will be added to your view, and you will be editing that display.','','none'),(9311,_binary 'Optionally, click the link next to <em>Display name</em> and enter a new name to be shown for this display in the administrative interface.','','none'),(9312,_binary 'Creating a new view','','none'),(9313,_binary 'Create a new view to list content or other items on your site.','','none'),(9314,_binary 'Click <em>Add view</em>.','','none'),(9315,_binary 'In the <em>View name</em> field, enter a name for the view, which is how it will be listed in the administrative interface.','','none'),(9316,_binary 'In <em>View settings</em> &gt; <em>Show</em>, select the base data type to display in your view. This cannot be changed later.','','none'),(9317,_binary 'Optionally, select or enter filtering, sorting, and page/block display settings; these can be added or changed later.','','none'),(9318,_binary 'Click <em>Save and edit</em>. Your view will be created; edit it following the steps in the related topics below.','','none'),(9319,_binary 'Editing an existing view display','','none'),(9320,_binary 'Edit an existing view display, to modify what data is displayed or how it is displayed.','','none'),(9321,_binary 'Under <em>Displays</em>, click the display you want to edit.','','none'),(9322,_binary 'For sections containing lists (such as <em>Fields</em> and <em>Filter criteria</em>), to modify or delete an existing item, click the name of the item. To add a new item, click <em>Add</em> in the drop-down list. To change the order of items, click <em>Rearrange</em> in the drop-down list.','','none'),(9323,_binary 'For sections containing individual settings (such as <em>Title</em> and <em>Format</em>), there are often two links for each setting. The first link shows the current value; 